'The sea is ours': land-encircled Bolivia hopes court will reopen away to Pacific
Marines patrol a masonry-covered naval quarters in La Paz.
Public buildings fly a sea blue flag.
Naval bases from Titicaca Lake to the Amazon are plastered with the slogan: "The sea is rightly ours.
It's a duty to get it back."
Throughout land-encircling Bolivia, the memory of the coastline they lost to Chile in a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century is still fresh – as is the need to sail back to the Pacific Ocean.
That hope is probably the highest it has been in decades, while Bolivia is waiting for a ruling by the international court on October 1, after 5 years of talks.
"Bolivia has the momentum, the spirit of unity and peace, and naturally expects the outcome with a positive attitude," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the ICC ruling on big screens across the country, hoping that the Hague tribunal will find in favor of Bolivia’s claim that – after decades of sporadic negotiations – Chile is obliged to negotiate to give Bolivia a sovereign passage to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president – facing a controversial battle for re-election next year – also has a lot that depends on Monday’s ruling.
"We are close to returning to the Pacific Ocean," he promised in late August.
But some analysts believe that it is unlikely that the court will decide in Bolivia’s favor – and that few will change if it does.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no power to allocate Chilean territory, and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of possible negotiations.
The fact that the IRH's ruling comes just six months after the last demonstrations shows that the case "was not complicated," says Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And instead of helping Bolivia's case, it may have slowed down over the past four years.
"The issue of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration," Zárate said.
Morales' aggressive rhetoric tapped any remaining Chilean goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will resume talks at some point, but it will be tremendously difficult to hold subsequent talks.
The two countries exchanged ambassadors in 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court's decision-making was extraordinarily swift.
On Monday, Bolivia will bring "an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile" and an opportunity to "end 139 years of differences with reciprocal benefits," he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales – still one of Latin America’s most popular presidents – used the maritime issue as a political crutch.
Bolivia will never give up its right to access the Pacific," he said.
"The verdict is an opportunity to see what we need to overcome the past."
