North Korea says they won't disarm unilaterally without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions exacerbated its mistrust of the United States and that the country would definitely not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons without such characteristics.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Body's annual General Assembly that North Korea has taken "significant benevolence measures" in the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, breaking down the nuclear test site, and pledging not to multiply nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"We don't see any consistent response from the U.S.," he said.
"Without any trust in the U.S., there will be no trust in our national security and under such circumstances we will certainly not unilaterally disarm first."
While Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" nuclear weapons removal approach that would reward North Korea if it took gradual steps, his words seemed meaningful by not unconditionally rejecting unilateral nuclear weapons removal as Pyongyang did in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong-Oen and Donald Trump at the very first summit between a US president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore when Kim pledged to work for "the destruction of nuclear weapons in the Korean peninsula" while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea wants a formal end to the Korean War of 1950-53, but the United States said Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also resisted requests for tight international sanctions against North Korea.
"The U.S. insists on the 'destruction of nuclear weapons first' and exerts more pressure by tightening the level of sanctions to achieve their goal in a compelling way, and even object to the 'declaration of the end of the war,'" Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can force us on our knees is a dream of people who are ignorant about us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions are exacerbating our mistrust."
Ri said nothing about plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader called attention to earlier this week at the United Nations.
Instead, the minister drew attention to three meetings over the past five months between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in, adding: "If the party in this issue of nuclear weapons destruction were South Korea and not the US, nuclear weapons destruction in the Korean Peninsula would not have reached such a dead end."
The tone of Ri's speech was nonetheless dramatically different from last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korea's rockets would be aimed at the U.S. landmass after "Mr. Evil President" Trump called Kim a "fire arrowman" on a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea last year, generously praised Kim for taking steps to disarm, but he said much work still needs to be done and that sanctions still remain there until North Korea destroys nuclear weapons.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn't have a time frame for this, saying "it doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years or five months."
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps they have taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that: "Application of sanctions by the Security Council must continue diligently and unremittingly until we realize the full, final, confirmed destruction of nuclear weapons."
The Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in an effort to dry up funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri on the outskirts of the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip there did not go well.
He left Pyongyang in July, saying that progress had been made, but North Korea accused him just hours later of making "gang-like claims."
North Korea pledged in a meeting with Moon to demolish a missile site and also a nuclear complex if the United States takes "consistent measures."
He said Kim told him that the "corresponding measures" he wants to see are security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore as well as steps towards normalizing relationship with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year is letting all its undergraduate students get more sleep in an effort to counteract the growing macho culture of studying through caffeine-driven "whole-day sessions."
An academic has found that students at the world's top university are often uninformed when it comes to the basics of how to care for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical Faculty and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end of that one girl approached me and said, 'Why are they telling me this first, in my senior year?'
She said no one has ever told her how important sleep is - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, presented for the first time this year, explains to students the basics of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as how they improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical Faculty and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after it was found that students were seriously deprived of sleep during the week.
The hour-long course involves a few interactive tasks.
In one section, there is a picture of a dormitory, where students need to click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise shoes and books to be told about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deprivation and the importance of a sleep time routine.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase risks of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know it won't change students' behavior immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know - just as you have the right to know what the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes are," Prof Czeisler added.
The culture of pride to "study all day" still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students has meant that sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
To make sure you get enough good quality sleep, a student's "secret weapon" should be to avoid stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, he said - even to avoid gaining weight, because sleep deprivation puts the brain in a starvation mode, which makes you feel hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course after he walked one of his classes last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to endeavor for a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all graduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the institution where people compete with each other.
Prof Czeisler recommended that students should consider setting an alarm for when they go to sleep, as well as when to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitted through electronic screens and LED lights, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm and cause you to struggle to touch the sheep.
