Almanac: The Inventor of the Geiger Counter
And now a page from our "Sunday Morning" almanac: 30 September 1882, today 136 years ago, and WE CONTINUE... the day on which the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device called the Geiger counter.
Since then, the Geiger counter has been a pillar of science, and it has also become a pillar in pop culture, as in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado," in which those two unlikely cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans played:
He said, "What on earth is this?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter used to detect radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you put these earphones on, you can even hear the effects of the atoms emitted by the radioactivity in the minerals.
Evans: "Goodbye, it's about to crack!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name lives on.
